What is BST Iterator actually trying to do?

       7
      / \
     3   15
        /  \
       9   20

Its inorder traversal is:

3 7 9 15 20

Now suppose someone asks:
"Give me the next smallest element every time I ask."

Like this:
iterator.next(); // 3
iterator.next(); // 7
iterator.next(); // 9
iterator.next(); // 15

instead of giving the whole traversal at once.

That's exactly what an iterator does.

Remember what next() is supposed to return:POP THE NODE,  The smallest unvisited element.

Final Iterator Logic
Whenever we pop a node:
Save answer
Move to its right child
Push all left nodes from there


class BSTIterator {
public:

    stack<TreeNode*> stack;

    // Push all left nodes into stack
    void pushAllLeft(TreeNode* node)
    {
        while(node)
        {
            stack.push(node);
            node = node->left;
        }
    }

    BSTIterator(TreeNode* root)
    {
        pushAllLeft(root);
    }

    // Returns true if there are more elements
    bool hasNext()
    {
        return !st.empty();
    }

    // Returns next smallest element
    int next() {
        TreeNode* currentNode = stack.top();
        st.pop();

        // Process right subtree
        if(currentNode->right)
        {
            pushAllLeft(currentNode->right);
        }

        return currentNode->data;
    }
};


